									</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

				<div class="comment-body"><p>This at least is correct:</p>
<p>&#8220;The reason that this whole thing started was because some fans discovered that fandom in general does not align with their views; they chose to drag mundane political issues into fandom; and they chose to try and buck the system by gaming it for both ideological and commercial reasons.&#8221;</p>
<p>The question is which fans those were.  I believe LC when he says that  SP #1 was a reaction to the whisper campaign against him 4 years ago.  </p>
<p>I also love the &#8220;fandom in general does not align.&#8221;  My experience over the last 40+ years of being a fan is that &#8220;fandom&#8221;, as a whole, does not align with any particular views.  SF/F fandom is incredibly diverse, politically.  That is why the lack of political diversity in recent nominees and winners was so striking to many of us.</p>
</div>

				<div class="reply">
				<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='index.html?replytocom=372812#respond' data-commentid="372812" data-postid="2177" data-belowelement="comment-372812" data-respondelement="respond" aria-label='Reply to Richard'>Reply</a>				</div><!-- .reply -->
			</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

